english:
  title: Epitaph for An Kyŏng-gong, Lord of Hŭngnŭng, Meritorious Subject in the Founding of Chosŏn, Grand Minister of Exhortation and Emolument
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The An clan traced its origins to the great families of Sunhŭng. An ancestor surnamed Sŏk, who obtained the examination degree, built his household through diligent study. Later he withdrew from the world, becoming a righteous gentleman of his village. He fathered Mun-jŏng Kong, whose name was Chu. Chu achieved success in the civil examinations of the Yuan court and served Korea, rising to Vice Chancellor of the Right and Lord of Hŭngnŭng, where he directed the Hall of Worthies. His literary and political talents made him renowned throughout his age. He fathered Mun-gan Kong, whose name was Chong-wŏn. Chong-wŏn passed the examinations in his youth and held many prestigious posts, eventually joining the highest councils. At the founding of our nation, drawing on his age and accumulated virtue, he was appointed Judge of the Gate Below and Great Scholar of the Jiphyŏn Hall, dying in office. Through his marriage to the daughter of Wŏn Sangssi Kim Hui-nam, three sons achieved examination success, earning him the title Lord of Kyŏnghye.

    This was our subject's father and mother. Our subject bore the name Kyŏng-gong with courtesy name Sun-bo. From childhood he received the teachings of his family, showing no trace of frivolous habits. His gentleness, righteousness, filial piety, and reverence were rooted in his nature. In the twenty-fifth year of Zhizheng, the year of Ŭlsa, he achieved distinction in the military examination. In the fifth year of Hongwu, the year of Imja, he received appointment as a minor official. The following year he was promoted to Knight-Commandant, concurrently serving as Censor-in-Ordinary. In the year Byŏngsin, holding the post of Vice Director of the Righteous Granary, he passed the examination for advanced scholars. He served in succession as Director of Records, Director of Laws, Vice Minister, Censor, and through his position as Court of Rites Gentleman, he rose through five promotions to Left Minister of the Three Offices. He was appointed Upper Guard-Commander and concurrent Judge of the Gate of Etiquette, with teaching responsibilities at the진현館. Soon he was transferred to Judge of the Collation Office, Knowledge Draftsman, and Minister of Rites. When moved to the Director of Laws, he showed compassion in judgment and reversed many unjust decisions. Sent out as magistrate of Hwangju, he nurtured his people as a parent nurtures children, such that when he departed, the people mourned his absence.

    In the fourth month of the year Imsin, he entered the Secret Chancery as Left Vice Counselor. In the seventh month, our Great Founder, responding to Heaven's mandate, carried out his revolution. Our subject, recognizing that the mandate had come to the Great Founder, joined with the generals and ministers in supporting him, advancing to Left Counselor. When the new administration was established, he rose to become a Meritorious Subject in the Founding, Chief Eunuch of the Central Chancellery. At this time, when all things were being created anew, our subject first served as the mouth and ear of government. His promulgation and reception of commands was clear and measured, and his wise counsels and secret deliberations brought great benefit. In the year Gyeyu he was promoted to Grand Censor of the Censorate, Minister of the Council of Evaluation, and Scholar of the Precious Text Pavilion. Our subject entered the Censorate twice, maintaining his integrity without wavering, his bearing grave and austere.

    In the year Gapsu, he mourned the passing of Mun-gan Kong. When the mourning period ended, he was enfeoffed as Lord of Hŭngnŭng with the rank of Counselor in Ordinary, while his honors and institutional position remained unchanged. In the fourth year of Yongnak, the year of Byŏngsu, he was appointed Judge of Kongan, with rank advanced to Counselor in Ordinary. He was transferred to Judge of Hansŏng with his rank raised again to Grand Precinct Chief. In the year Mucha, he experienced mourning for his father. In his care of his father's medicines and in fulfilling the rites of burial, he showed such absolute sincerity and filial devotion that all who witnessed it were moved to reverence.

    In the year Gyŏngin, when the Grand Progenitor visited Songdo, our subject was commanded to remain as Administrator of Kaesŏng. In the year Byŏngshin, he was specially appointed Grand Minister of the Precious Text Pavilion with rank of Grand Minister Who Assists the Nation and Promotes Emolument, and was elevated to Lord of a Princedom.

    When our subject held office, he devoted himself entirely to the concerns of state, bringing order to all affairs. As a grand minister, he maintained steady composure and grave bearing, becoming a model of propriety for the court. Our subject served as Inspector of Kyŏngsang Province and Inspector of Chŏlla and Hwanghae provinces. Following the established way, he disseminated education, suppressing the strong and protecting the weak, employing lenient and simple methods without harshness, such that his regions achieved good order.

    On the tenth day of the first month of the year Sinch'uk, he passed away peacefully at home at the age of seventy-five. When our subject fell ill, the Grand Progenitor and our present Lord urgently dispatched royal physicians to treat him and sent envoys to inquire after his condition. When news of his passing reached both palaces, great lamentation was expressed. The court granted exceptional funeral honors and gave him the posthumous name Good Measure. On the twenty-seventh day of the second month, the day Gyŏngshin, he was laid to rest on the hillside of Paeksa Valley in Kŭmch'ŏn.

    Our subject possessed a heart of uprightness and trustworthiness, conducting himself with careful propriety. He never altered his bearing to follow the trends of the time, nor did he stand apart from others to display uniqueness. In his dealings with people, he was ever sincere and truthful, never feigning. Though his inner knowledge was keen, he never spoke of others' faults. His humble virtue shone the brighter as his position rose higher. From youth he despised ostentation, devoted himself to simplicity. In his later years, living in retirement and seldom venturing out, whenever guests arrived he would surely offer them wine, seeking only their pleasure without extravagance. His heart was placid as still water, without contention with others.

    Our subject had three siblings, all of great renown, yet all died young without male heirs. Only our subject enjoyed the blessing of Heaven, becoming an elder statesman of the realm. His grandsons and great-grandsons flourished abundantly, and his house prospered ever more greatly. Truly the rewards of accumulated goodness are never in vain.

    His lady wife, Chŏng of Ouch'ŏn, was the daughter of Mun-jŏng Kong Sadо. As the primary wife of a meritorious subject, she received the title Honored Quiet Household Mistress. She bore one son named Sun, now serving as Grand Precinct Chief, Minister of Revenue, and Grand Scholar of the Precious Text Pavilion. He married the daughter of the Counselor of State Chŏng Kwŏn and fathered four sons and three daughters. The eldest son, Sung-jik, is Upper Guard-Commander of the Yongyang Guard. The second son, Sung-sŏn, is Chief Eunuch of the Secretariat and achieved first place in the examinations of the year Gyŏngja. The third son, Sung-sin, is Guard-Commander of the Martial Valor Guard and Official of the Central Chancellery. The fourth son, Sung-hyo, is Judge of the Central Guard. The eldest daughter married Great Censor of the Censorate Yi Suk-chi. The second married Judge of the Gate of Etiquette Cho Hye. The third married Censor Yi of the Censorate Kim Chun-rye. There are numerous great-great-grandchildren.

    The Upper Guard-Commander married the daughter of Lord of P'yŏngbuk Cho Gyŏn and fathered one daughter, who married Judge Pak Kang. The Chief Eunuch married the daughter of Upper Guard-Commander Song Ch'ŏn-u and fathered two sons and two daughters. The eldest son is Hun, the second is Ŭi. The eldest daughter married Governor Kyŏngch'ang Kim Suk, the second married Court of the Crown Prince's Left Secretariat Cho Sŏk-mun.

    The Guard-Commander married the daughter of Magistrate of Kwangju Yi Suk-ya and fathered one son and four daughters. The son is Chŏn. The eldest daughter married Dye Records Official Ch'oe Min, the others are young. The Judge married the daughter of Concurrently Eunuch of the Central Chancellery Yi Suk-myo and fathered two sons and three daughters. The eldest son is Kyŏm, the second is Nŭl, the daughters are all young. The Great Censor fathered one daughter, who married Official of Insun Garrison Yi Kye-hyŏn. The Judge of Etiquette fathered five sons and three daughters. The eldest son, Chidang, is Official of the Ancestral Temple Shrine. The second, Chiŭn, is Deputy Secretary. The third is Chihа, the fourth is Chihan, the fifth is Chichu. The eldest daughter married Scholar Cho Kye-bŏm, the rest are young. The Censor fathered four sons and four daughters. The eldest son is Maeng-jŏl, the second is Maeng-ŭi, the third is Maeng-ryŏm, the fourth is Maeng-ch'i. The eldest daughter married Scholar Hong To-sang, the rest are young. There are numerous great-great-grandchildren. Judge Pak fathered one son and three daughters, all young. Official Kim fathered one son and one daughter, young. Chŏn fathered two daughters. Records Official fathered one daughter, young. Shrine Official fathered one son, young. Deputy Secretary fathered one son and two daughters, all young.

    Alas, how flourishing this may be called! The epitaph reads:

    The lofty White Mountains
    Rise toward the azure heavens above,
    Cradling rare essence and nurturing luminous worth—
    Seven ministers and five dukes they bore.
    They begat Good Measure,
    Whose heirs would inherit the precious legacy.
    With loyalty and filial piety,
    Traversing every path with reverent steps.
    His merit is graven on bell and cauldron,
    His name carries weight among the robed officials.
    The virtue of ages ripened
    Mirrors itself in diviner's craft.
    In life he received signal favor,
    In death, honorable observance.
    Slander and praise, beginning and end—
    All shine eternal on history's page.
    Children and children's children in succession,
    Blessings unending, fortune unfailing.
    Words carved in stone interred here
    To show all those yet to come.
